When NYC’s affluent ‘young urban creatives’ departed the city during the COVID-19 pandemic,  many began to recognize they’d long felt overdue for a change of pace. Once settled in, some found these new lifestyles preferable to city life and chose not to return, effectively retiring to greener pastures.

Brooklyn’s dead
 And Kingston’s booming

During the early days of the COVID-19 pandemic of 2020-21, Kingston, NY— a town 90 minutes north of the city— served as the epicenter of a sudden upstate real estate boom as panicked yuccies fled their expensive Brooklyn condos for safer, more idyllic lifestyles in the Hudson Valley.

That’s a real nice neck
 Can I make it stop zooming?

This lyric is an interpolation of “A little less neck / Can I make you stop breathing?” from the Holy Ghost! song It Gets Dark.



Alex Frankel and Nicholas Millhiser of Holy Ghost! also receive writing credits on this song, with Frankel producing in addition.

annotations:
You gotta have boots
 If you wanna lift those bootstraps

A paraphrasing of a Martin Luther King Jr quote
“It’s all right to tell a man to lift himself by his own bootstraps, but it is cruel jest to say to a bootless man that he ought to lift himself by his own bootstraps.”

A comment on the advice given to many (often poor) people about how they need to “lift themselves up by the bootstraps” if they want to be successful which, in the metaphor, assumes the person is able to afford boots. Mirroring how many people can’t afford the tools and opportunities needed to pull themselves out of poverty regardless of their work ethic.
You can do a lot with four American dollars

4AD is a British independent record label that released this album, as well as some of U.S. Girls' previous albums.

The classic American success story often mentions someone coming to this country with some absurdly low amount of money (in this case $4) and then turning that into riches. The reality is that $4 USD is not even close to enough to live off of and being able to turn that into wealth would not only require a good work ethic but also a tremendous amount of luck which is often ignored when wealthy people explain their own success, framing it as their business acumen and work ethic being all that was needed.
Rubles
The currency unit of Russia, Belarus and Transnistria
Yen
The official currency of Japan
Rupees

The name for the currencies of India, Indonesia, the Maldives, Mauritius, Nepal, Pakistan, Seychelles, and Sri Lanka, and of former currencies of Afghanistan, all Arab states of the Persian Gulf (as the Gulf rupee), British East Africa, Burma, German East Africa, the Trucial States, and Tibet.

annotations:
A cage holds you
 We’ve all got one we call home
 But in the event of a 9-1-1
 Who holds the key is what you need to know

In the aforementioned film, Citizen Kane, “Rosebud” is revealed to be representative of Charles Foster Kane’s lost childhood –  a repressed desire that was never fulfilled and a crucial piece of himself he never got to explore.

This verse depicts one’s own repressed demon as a locked birdcage keeping one’s mind from flying free. U.S. Girls tells us that in the event of a great crisis or emergency, knowing how to think freely will win you the day. Paired with the chorus, the track urges that although it will be hard to do, you must confront your demons and find the key to your cage.



Poppy, “This Birdcage” (2017)
There’s a Rosebud for you and one for me

This is a reference to the famous 1941 film Citizen Kane, which was an indelible game-changer in the world of cinema thanks to the direction of Orson Welles. The whole film revolves around the cryptic dying words of newspaper magnate Charles Foster Kane – “Rosebud.” Concluding the autopsy of Kane’s entire life, the meaning of “Rosebud” is finally revealed, but only to the audience. In the film itself, only Kane knows the word’s meaning.

In this line, U.S. Girls is implying that we all have a “Rosebud” – something which is key to understanding yourself. She prompts us, much like the film does, to “use those keys and take a drive through the back alleys of your mind.”
